This article is part of the Opinion Today newsletter. You can sign up here to receive the newsletter each weekday.

The historian Kevin Kruse made a thoughtful Thanksgiving suggestion on Twitter this week. He encouraged people to reach out to “someone whose creative work means a lot to you” — like a novelist, artist or a musician — and to tell them. Many of them work hard and deal frequently with rejection, Kruse noted. “A quick, kind word can go a long, long way,” he said.

Inspired by that idea, I want to say thank you today to some other hard-working people who deserve more recognition than they often receive: teachers.

Regular readers know how important I think education is. It lifts families out of poverty more frequently than anything else. It can also bring less tangible joys, by introducing people to new books, art, music and ideas. And when education succeeds, it is almost always because of teachers. I was lucky to have several great teachers when I was in school, including:

Ms. Sandler, in first and second grade, who changed my life by making math seem like the world’s most exciting language;

Mr. Bienstock, who taught me how to study and grapple with history;

Mr. Schiller, whose wit, wisdom, humor and passion were especially effective when used in the service of explaining why I was wrong;

Mrs. Bowen, Ms. Kornstein and Ms. Rossano, a Murderer’s Row of high-school math teachers, whose mnemonics I can still sing.

To all of them — and to other teachers, too — I give thanks today.

Please pass the umbrage. Since the 2016 election, a new cottage industry in journalism has sprung up: articles that offer advice for how to talk politics at Thanksgiving with relatives who have different views from yours. On this week’s episode of “The Argument” podcast, Ross Douthat, Michelle Goldberg and I talk about our objections to those articles. I offer a very specific alternate suggestion: You should feel free to enjoy a holiday meal with your family and not talk about politics.
